# Agent Evals: {{PROJECT_NAME}}

<!--
Purpose: small, concrete tasks used to check that the agent still behaves
correctly on this project, and specifically that it applies what it has
learned. Evals exist to catch two kinds of regression:
1. Precision regression — the agent starts making a mistake it used to
   avoid (e.g. running an unverified command, editing a forbidden file).
2. Learning regression — a promoted rule (Status: active in
   learned-rules.md) stops being followed.

When to run these:
- After any change to the adapter (project-profile.md, learned-rules.md,
  command-map.md) or to skills/agents that shape behavior.
- Immediately after promoting a candidate rule to active, to confirm the
  agent now follows it.
- Periodically (e.g. weekly, or before a release) as a regression check.

This file starts with no evals. Add one per rule or per recurring
failure that is important enough to verify automatically or by hand.

Transcripts & judging:
- The executing model saves a run transcript to .agent-os/eval-transcripts/<eval-name-slug>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md.
- A stronger, independent model grades the run via the judge-agent-eval skill; its notes land in the Judge column.
- Rows recorded without judge notes show "unjudged" — treat an unjudged pass as provisional.
- Judge rows are structured: the runner enforces --judge-model + a real transcript, and refuses a judge model equal to the executing model.
-->

